4. Data Quality Challenges (Real-World Characteristics)

Because the dataset was derived from real job advertisements, several practical data issues were observed:

Missing values: Around 15% of postings did not specify education requirements.

Formatting inconsistencies: Some salaries appeared as hourly wages and required annual conversion.

Salary ranges: Using midpoint estimates introduces approximation noise.

Textual variations and typos: Examples include “Bachlor” instead of “Bachelor’s”.

Subjective skill counting: The number of programming skills depends on how explicitly technologies are listed in the posting.

These imperfections accurately reflect real industry data and provide valuable material for data cleaning, preprocessing, and feature engineering in later stages of the machine learning workflow.

5. Machine Learning Applications
Primary Task: Regression

Objective:
Predict the exact annual salary based on:

Experience level

Education requirement

Work arrangement

Company size

Technical skill demand

This supports algorithms such as:

Linear Regression

Decision Tree Regressor

Random Forest Regressor

Alternative Task: Classification

Salaries may be categorized into:

High Pay: Above $100,000

Standard Pay: $100,000 or below

This enables binary classification models useful for job market analysis and salary prediction tools.

Additional Analytical Opportunities

Feature importance analysis to determine the strongest salary predictors.

Comparison of remote vs. on-site compensation trends.

Exploratory data visualization for industry insights.

6. Conclusion

This assignment provided hands-on experience in collecting, structuring, and documenting a real-world dataset suitable for machine learning.
By manually extracting salary information from live technology job postings, the dataset captures authentic data challenges, including:

Missing information

Inconsistent formatting

Estimation uncertainty

In future stages, the dataset will undergo:

Data cleaning and preprocessing

Categorical encoding and scaling

Model training and evaluation

This process will help bridge the gap between theoretical machine learning concepts and practical real-world data analysis, strengthening foundational data science skills.